Narrative:
At 2:23pm:  WeRide driverless vehicle (vehicle 1) with a safety operator seated in front passenger seat, was travelling 45mph without much traffic ahead when a BMW x3 (vehicle 2) travelling in the adjacent left lane and in the same direction, merged into vehicle 1's left front quarter panel. Vehicle 1 and Vehicle 2 sustained moderate damages.
After discussing the incident with vehicle 2's driver, they admitted they were attempting to make an upcoming right turn off the expressway. They initiated 2 consecutive right lane changes abruptly before hitting vehicle 1 on their last attempted lane change.
After the initial impact, vehicle 1 was forced out of the initial lane, onto a divide, and ultimately came to a stop on the shoulder of the expressway. At this time both occupants of vehicle 1 and vehicle 2 were able to assess respective damages and exchange information. It was determined that there were no injuries. WeRide Vehicle (Vehicle 1) required a tow back to the facility.

On February [XXX], 2025 at 6:11 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco was in a collision involving debris on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound in the leftmost lane on [XXX] when the front passenger side tire of the Waymo AV made contact with a piece of debris that was in the roadway, causing the Waymo AV to slow to a stop. The passenger car traveling directly behind the Waymo AV also slowed to a stop, causing a second passenger car traveling behind the first passenger car to also slow. While the second passenger car was slowing, a third passenger car traveling behind the second passenger car began to merge into the center lane and the front driver side of the third passenger car made contact with the rear passenger side of the second passenger car. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The second and third passenger cars sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On May [XXX], 2025 at 8:00 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV came to a stop facing westbound on [XXX] at a stop sign at the intersection at [XXX] in a location where vegetation to the left of the AV created occlusion of the approaching near-side sidewalk. After coming to a stop at the stop line, the Waymo AV began moving forward into the intersection at [XXX] when a cyclist that had been traveling northwest on the near-side sidewalk along [XXX] entered the crosswalk and the front tire of the bike made contact with the front driver side of the Waymo AV. The cyclist fell to the ground.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The cyclist later informed Waymo of a minor injury.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was traveling south on [XXX], slowing and preparing to make a right turn onto [XXX] in San Francisco. At that time, an approaching e-scooterist was also traveling south on [XXX] in the curb lane offset from the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle braked to a stop as the e-scooterist was beginning to enter the intersection. The e-scooterist then made contact with the right rear side of the stopped Zoox vehicle, and the e-scooterist fell to the ground next to the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then started to move and completed the right turn onto [XXX], coming to a stop a short distance down [XXX]. The e-scooterist then walked themself and the e-scooter over to the sidewalk, where they were met by a member of the Zoox operations team, and they reported "[REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] chipped tooth and jaw pain." The e-scooterist declined medical attention and rode their e-scooter from the scene after exchanging information. There was no damage to the Zoox vehicle and the police were not called.

On March [XXX], 2025 at 1:05 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was parked near the curb facing east on [XXX] for a rider drop-off.  The rider opened the rear passenger door and was exiting the Waymo AV when an SUV reversed out of a driveway to the right of the Waymo AV and the rear driver side of the SUV made contact with the open rear passenger door of the stationary Waymo AV resulting in the door of the Waymo AV making contact with the rider's leg.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The passenger in the Waymo AV alleged a minor injury and was not belted at the time of the collision as they were preparing to exit the Waymo AV.  
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On February [XXX], 2025 at 11:43 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on[XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was travelling northbound on[XXX] and came to a stop at a red traffic light at the intersection with [XXX]. A passenger car also traveling northbound on S. Sherbourne Drive approached the Waymo AV from behind and the front of the passenger car made contact with the rear of the stationary Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Neither vehicle sustained damage. The passenger in the Waymo AV alleged a minor injury.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On January [XXX], 2025 at 9:14 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX].
The Waymo AV was travelling eastbound on [XXX] in the center lane when an SUV travelling eastbound in the opposing travel lanes began to approach the Waymo AV from behind and to the left. The SUV then began to maneuver into the left eastbound travel lane, and continued into the center lane occupied by the Waymo AV, and the front passenger side of the SUV made contact with the drivers side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Neither vehicle sustained damage. On February 5, 2025, Waymo received an allegation of a minor injury from the passenger in the Waymo AV.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

The Mercedes-Benz vehicle was traveling southbound in a parking lot located at [XXX], Santa Clara, CA 95051 when the driver engaged L3 ADS system for a few seconds. The driver then disengaged L3 ADS and continued to drive in conventional mode. The vehicle was manually braked and came to a complete stop. At this time, a Chevrolet Camaro parked perpendicular to the right of the vehicle, reversed from their parking spot and made contact with the right middle panel of the Mercedes-Benz.

The subject Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driving in the back parking lot of the [XXX] in Santa Clara, CA (parallel to the [XXX]). The Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driven in conventional mode when the driver engaged L3 ADS for a few seconds. The driver then disengaged L3 ADS and continued to drive in conventional mode. The vehicle was manually braked to a stop adjacent to vehicles parked in the parking lot, and perpendicular to a parked Chevrolet Camaro. The driver in the Mercedes-Benz then shifted into Park ("P") via the gearshift lever. While the Mercedes-Benz vehicle was stopped, the Chevrolet Camaro reversed out of its parking space and contacted the Mercedes-Benz vehicle at the right rear door. As a result, the right rear corner of the Chevrolet Camaro and the right rear passenger door of the Mercedes-Benz vehicle sustained minor damage. There were no reported injuries to any of the occupants.

On December [XXX], 2024 in Houston, Texas, a Nuro vehicle operating in manual made contact with a curb. On November [XXX] at 1:27pm, Car 1 (weride av) - while ADS Engaged -  was making a legal, protected, left turn from [XXX]. Car 1, turning onto [XXX], performed the turn from the second lane from the left and was travelling 11 mph when Car 1 then slowed down while still in the intersection. It is at this time Car 1's safety driver disengaged ADS of Car 1 this put car 1 into manual mode. It is at this time when car 2 (Ford f-150 XLT), traveling at 18 mph, approximately less than 13 feet away from Car 1 and also making a left turn from [XXX] within the same lane as car 1, struck and rear ended car 1 while both cars were still in the intersection.
At the time of impact Car 1 (Weride AV) ADS was not engaged.
Car 1 sustained minor damage to its rear bumper and car 2 sustained minor damage to front bumper. Both parties pulled over to exchange information.
Car 2 did not provide Registration and Insurance for their respective car. Car 2's driver did give us driver's license information but the driver of the vehicle (car 2) at the time of the incident was a different person than that represented on the driver's license presented.
There was no injuries, no property damage and no police were called.

On November [XXX], 2024 Waymo received notice of an allegation that a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Los Angeles, California may have been in a low-speed collision with a non-motorist (pedestrian) on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
On November [XXX], 2024 at 4:04 AM PT a Waymo AV operating in Los Angeles, California was traveling northwest on [XXX] when it began to slow to yield to a pedestrian crossing the street ahead from right to left. After the pedestrian had crossed the path of the Waymo AV, the Waymo AV began to accelerate slightly then immediately began to slow again as the pedestrian turned around and approached the Waymo AV. As the Waymo AV was slowing, the pedestrian may have made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV. 
At the time of the possible impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The pedestrian later claimed to have a minor injury.  The Waymo AV did not sustain any damage. 
Even though this event may involve intentional contact by the pedestrian and the occurrence of actual contact between the Waymo AV and the pedestrian is not clear, Waymo is reporting this event as a crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user (pedestrian) influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and reportedly sustained a minor injury as a result of the event. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative:
At approximately 12:42 PM CT on October [XXX], 2024, the Beep-operated [XXX] with VIN [XXX] (P139) was involved in a minor, non-injury collision. The shuttle was operating under a valid permission as documented in the change letter dated September [XXX], 2024. 
Traveling Southbound on [XXX], P139 stopped at the three-way intersection just north of the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX]. After the operator cleared the shuttle to proceed through the intersection under automated control, a trailing white sedan made contact at low speed with the rear of P139, having failed to come to a complete stop behind the shuttle. P139 continued through the intersection before stopping at the [XXX] stop station. The white sedan turned onto [XXX] and left the scene. 
There was one passenger onboard at the time of the incident. They were uninjured and alighted the shuttle without concern at the [XXX] stop station. P139 was removed from service for inspection. The shuttle sustained minor cosmetic damage.

The May Mobility vehicle was at a designated pick up location waiting for a passenger to get on board. Because of an unprotected turn required to get to the stop, the autonomous vehicle operator took over manually. As the vehicle waited parked at the stop, a car in a parking space in front of the stop backed up into the May vehicle at 2mph. This impact occurs 25 seconds after last being in autonomous mode.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was stopped for a red traffic light on northbound [XXX] while preparing to turn left onto westbound [XXX] in San Francisco. After the light turned green the Zoox vehicle began to move forward and then slowed gradually to yield to a pedestrian with right of way in the crosswalk on [XXX]. Just as the Zoox vehicle slowed to almost a stop (0.2 mph), a skateboarder quickly approached the rear of the Zoox vehicle extending their left arm forward and making contact with the right rear corner of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy and brought the vehicle to a stop. The skateboarder initially told the Zoox vehicle operator they were not injured but later mentioned they "smacked" their hand and it was "bruised." When asked, however, they declined medical attention. The Zoox vehicle did not sustain damage. The police were not called. The Zoox vehicle camera footage shows that the skateboarder was looking at their cell phone and did not appear to have been looking ahead at the roadway before the time of contact.The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

The vehicle in front of the customer's vehicle slowed down abruptly on the freeway and the customer immediately stepped on the brake to slow her vehicle down. The customer's vehicle slowed down in a straight line without locking-up of the wheels, indicating ABS worked as intended. The customer's vehicle was then rear-ended by the vehicle which was unable to stop resulting in a minor fender-bender on the freeway. No injuries were reported and both vehicles sustained only scratches and were able to drive away from the scene.

In conjunction with Motional's filing of the subject incident, and according to statement(s) provided in Motional's incident report:
A Motional AV was operating in Las Vegas, Nevada, in autonomous mode with a safety driver at the wheel and an engineer in the front passenger seat.
The AV was eastbound on [XXX], approaching the intersection with [XXX], in the furthest left of five lanes (lane one), a dedicated left turn lane.  Another vehicle, originally traveling in a middle through-traffic lane (lane three), had entered lane two, also a dedicated left turn lane, and come to a stop almost perpendicular to the flow of traffic.  As the AV approached the other vehicle began moving from lane two into lane one without signaling.  The safety driver took control, turning the steering wheel to the left to create space from the other vehicle, momentarily bringing the AV's left front wheel onto a median curb before safely returning to the roadway after the AV had passed the other vehicle.
There were no injuries or property damage other than a minor tire scuff.  law enforcement was not involved.

The May vehicle is approaching a lane change. It signals the lane change appropriately early and begins to gradually decelerate for the change. The trailing SUV continues to accelerate while the May vehicle is simultaneously decelerating, and eventually changes lanes directly into the May vehicle. Trailing SUV drives away without slowing meaningfully, disappearing around an upcoming turn. May vehicle deceleration never exceeds -1.3m/s2, so there is no plausible reason a responsible driver would not have had adequate time to adjust their speed or path to avoid a collision.

May vehicle was waiting at the red light of [XXX] and [XXX]. The May vehicle was stopped and was 2nd behind the stop line. The van behind the May vehicle was also stopped. Van driver removed their foot from the brake pedal, idling into the May vehicle at a low rate of speed.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), was completing a mission traveling southwest on [XXX] in San Francisco. As the vehicle was completing its mission and slowed to a near stop, the Zoox vehicle operator identified an oncoming bicycle, disengaged from autonomy, and braked the Zoox vehicle to a full stop in its lane. The bicyclist crossed into the oncoming traffic lane occupied by the Zoox vehicle and continued rapidly while steering directly towards the front of the Zoox vehicle. The bicycle made contact with the front bumper of the stationary Zoox vehicle and the bicyclist made contact with the hood of the Zoox vehicle and fell to the ground. The police and emergency responders arrived at the scene and the bicyclist was transported to a hospital. The police report describes injuries to the bicyclist as "loss of consciousness, complaint of pain to back, knee, and toe nail". This 10-Day update provides complete information to date for this incident.

May vehicle was parked in autonomous mode at a rider stop when a VRU on a bicycle approached from the north, coming towards the vehicle. Bicycle was on the wrong side of the road and appeared to be weaving. There were no other vehicles nearby and the bicycle had significant room to avoid the May vehicle. However, the bicyclist came into contact with the driver side of the May vehicle, resulting in some minor damage to the May vehicle. After contact, the bicyclist appeared uninjured, got up and left the scene on the bicycle.

On July [xxx], 2024, at 12:59 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in [XXX], California was involved in an alleged collision with a non-motorist (cyclist) at a parking garage exit on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was exiting a parking garage onto [XXX], between [XXX] and [XXX]. As the Waymo AV approached the garage exit, it stopped for a cyclist who was approaching from the left. The Waymo AV remained stationary as the cyclist passed in front of the vehicle, slowed, and appeared to begin to dismount. The cyclist then reached out a hand and made contact with the front passenger side of the stationary Waymo AV, backed the bicycle up slightly, dropped the bicycle, then fell to the ground. 
At the time of the possible impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present. The cyclist received medical attention at the scene and was reportedly transported to a hospital by local emergency services. The Waymo AV did not sustain any damage.

This incident occurred near Streetman, TX on [XXX] at approximately 3:03 PM CT on February [XXX], 2024. The Aurora vehicle was operating in autonomy at the time. Conditions were clear. As the Aurora vehicle was driving in its lane at 62 mph, a box truck veered into the lane of the Aurora vehicle. The box truck's mirror appeared to make contact with the back of the trailer that the Aurora Driver was pulling. At this time, we are not aware of any injuries, and camera footage appears to show that the box truck continued to drive. From the post-trip inspection, there was not any visible trailer damage. Before the collision, the Aurora Driver was driving straight in its lane and passing the box truck. Shortly thereafter, the box truck began to encroach into the lane of the Aurora Driver. The Aurora Driver detected the box truck's encroachment into the Aurora vehicle's lane and initiated a nudge away from the box truck to provide space. The Aurora Driver detected the collision and made the decision to initiate an incident response, but before it could execute that response, the Vehicle Operator took over control of the system and proceeded in manual. The Aurora vehicle then re-engaged in autonomy approximately two minutes later. 
The Vehicle Operator did not visually observe the collision, assumed the reaction of the Aurora Driver to be a software anomaly, and reported the vehicle nudge through the standard annotation protocol rather than through the incident response protocols. The incident was identified at approximately 1:03 PM CT on February 2, 2024, through a review of Aurora's data logs.

A Ghost ADS-equipped car was driving engaged Northbound on [XXX]. As always, there were two safety drivers in the car. Traffic was moving in all four lanes at or near the speed limit. The Ghost vehicle was in the right-middle lane. Another vehicle (the "lead" car) entered into the Ghost car's lane from the right. While there were numerous vehicles ahead of the Ghost car before that vehicle entered the lane, the lead vehicle blocked the view of the lane before it. Throughout the incident, traffic in the other three lanes continued at a steady pace.
When the lead vehicle entered into the lane ahead of the Ghost car, the Ghost car applied the brakes to accommodate the intrusion and then continued to match the speed of the lead car. The lead car suddenly slammed the brakes. The Ghost car followed suit, reducing its speed from 19 mps (42.5 mph) to 4.7 mps (10.5 mph) within the next three seconds. The Ghost car was able to match the rapid speed reduction of the lead car and avoid contact.
The driver following the Ghost car was not able to respond as quickly as the Ghost ADS. When the following driver began to apply the brakes, the car was about five meters behind and was traveling at 6.5 mps. At the point of impact, the Ghost vehicle was traveling at 4.78 mps (10.7 mph), matching the lead car. There were no injuries. The vehicles suffered only cosmetic damage, the drivers exchanged information, and the Ghost safety drivers returned to home base in conventional mode.

As the Nissan Sentra and the AV proceeded through the intersection after the light turned green, a pedestrian entered the crosswalk on the opposite side of [XXX] across from the vehicles and proceeded through the intersection against a red light. The pedestrian passed completely through the AVs lane of travel but stopped mid-crosswalk in front of the Nissan Sentra. Shortly thereafter, the Nissan Sentra made contact with the pedestrian, deflecting the pedestrian in front of the AV. The May vehicle was traveling eastbound on [XXX] in autonomy. The vehicles internal facing cameras show that the operator started to fall asleep while applying physical input to the steering wheel. The road started to bend to the left. The physical input from the operator was enough to deviate the vehicle from its intended path but not enough to trigger an intervention and take the vehicle out of autonomy. The vehicle, going straight as the road curved, then struck the curb, resulting in minor vehicle damage. Due to the vehicle being off path, the vehicle begins to stop. This occurs as the operator wakes up. The operator was not injured and no third parties were impacted or otherwise affected by the incident. 
The local May Mobility site staff did not notice any signs of fatigue from this operator prior to going out in the vehicle. The operator had responded to audio check-ins from site staff at a regular interval. We are exploring additional risk mitigation options for in-cabin health monitoring, in addition to the existing cameras and radio check-ins.

Narrative:
At Approximately 12:39 PM, the Beep Command Center (BCC) informed the LYNX dispatch center that another autonomous shuttle operating on the same route (VIN: VG9A2CB2CJV[XXX]) was being taken out of service due to insufficient battery charge to continue operation. The BCC later informed LYNX dispatch at 12:49PM that the second shuttle operating on route, P131, would also be returning to storage after the operator completed its current loop. At Approximately 12:52 PM, P131 approached the [XXX] stop within the designated Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) operating lane. The shuttle remained stopped for approximately two (2) and a half minutes while three (3) passengers alighted, and two (2) additional passengers boarded the shuttle. During that period, approximately two (2) minutes after stopping to service passengers, a LYNX bus pulled behind P131. Approximately thirty (30) seconds later, the LYNX bus exited the BRT lane and proceeded into the public travel lane alongside the BRT lane. As the LYNX bus entered the public travel lane, the safety driver onboard P131 engaged the autonomous drive system, and the shuttle proceeded in the BRT lane. After both vehicles had begun moving, P131 in the BRT lane and the LYNX bus in the public travel lane, the LYNX bus reentered the BRT lane encroaching on the shuttles path. The bus failed to provide adequate clearance and contacted the left front side of P131. Both vehicles stopped in the BRT lane after the collision. 
Within five (5) minutes of the collision, all passengers had safely alighted from the shuttle with no reported injuries and left the scene without giving statements. At approximately 2:20PM, the City of Orlando Police Department (OPD) arrived on scene to investigate the incident. Beep and LYNX supervisors were on scene to support the investigation. OPD collected statements from both the Beep safety driver and LYNX bus driver. The LYNX supervisor provided OPD access to the LYNX bus camera footage on scene, at which point the investigating officer made a verbal indication that the LYNX bus driver appeared to be at fault for the collision. 
Beeps safety driver was subsequently subjected to a standard post-collision drug and alcohol screening. 
1.The safety driver did not exhibit complete situational awareness and per their after-incident interview, failed to notice the bus prior to departing the station. Had the attendant continued to look and check behind/alongside P131 prior to departing the station,
the collision may have been avoided.
2.The safety driver attempted to stop the shuttle by disengaging the ADS using the HMI rather than using the emergency stop button. Use of the emergency stop would have increased the deceleration rate to 5 m/s2, decreasing the stopping distance of the shuttle. However, it is not clear whether use of the emergency stop would have fully avoided the collision given the point at which the LYNX LYMMO bus entered the BRT lane.
3.Deficiencies in the standard operating procedures (SOP) between LYNX and Beep allowed for a bus to be deployed onto the service at the same time as P131. Beep communicated to LYNX that both shuttles were exiting the service area. However, LYNX did not wait for final confirmation that both vehicles had left the route prior to dispatching the LYMMO bus involved in the incident, nor did LYNX notify Beep that a bus had been dispatched.
Additional information available upon request.

Narrative:
VIN # VG9A2CB2CIV[XXX] 
At approximately 5:54 p.m. on Wednesday, August [XXX], 2023, P84, travelling eastbound on [XXX], approached the three-way stop at [XXX] and [XXX]. P84 arrived at the intersection at the same time as two other vehicles: a grey van heading northbound on [XXX] and a red sedan heading westbound on [XXX]. The safety driver yielded to the northbound vehicle, which proceeded to make a right-hand turn eastbound onto [XXX]. After allowing the intersection to clear, the safety driver onboard P84 confirmed that it was safe for the shuttle to proceed through the intersection. As the shuttle entered the intersection, a second vehicle travelling northbound on [XXX], a white sedan, entered the intersection intending a left-hand turn onto westbound [XXX]. Both vehicles entered the intersection simultaneously, subsequently colliding at a low rate of speed in the middle of the intersection.  
At approximately 5:57 p.m., the Beep Command Center (BCC) was informed by the safety driver that P84 was involved in a minor collision with another vehicle at the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX]. The incident response protocol was initiated, and a supervisor dispatched to the scene. Local law enforcement (San Francisco Police Department) was contacted to report the collision but declined to respond given the minor nature of the collision, directing both parties to exchange information. After the Beep supervisor arrived on scene at approximately 6:49 p.m., the safety driver and supervisor removed the shuttle from the roadway and exchanged insurance information with the driver of the other vehicle. 
Damage to both vehicles was noted to be very minor. The shuttle sustained light scuffs, chips, and small paint transfer. The other vehicle sustained a small dent on the fender. Neither vehicle required towing, and both were safely driven from the scene. 
Beeps safety driver was subsequently subjected to a standard post-collision drug & alcohol screening which has since cleared.  
Contributing Factors 
Based on an analysis of the available evidence, Beep has determined the following factors may have contributed to the higher likelihood of a collision occurring in this instance: 
1.The white sedan failed to yield to P84 in accordance with California state law governing intersection priority.
2.The slight bend in P84s path to accommodate the lane shift through the intersection may have reduced the available stopping distance as the white sedan was not perceived as an obstacle in P84s path until it proceeded further into the intersection.
Incident Findings 
Beep developed the following findings regarding this incident:
1.P84 behaved as expected, detecting and maintaining awareness of the white sedan in the moments preceding the collision, commanding hard braking maneuver, and achieving a 3m/s2 deceleration rate once the white sedan encroached on P84s path.
2.The safety driver observed California state law and had the right of way when releasing P84 into the intersection.
3.The safety driver could have avoided the collision by using the emergency stop. The safety driver indicated that they were aware of the other vehicle through the duration of the incident and were aware of the proper procedure in this scenario but panicked in the moment.
Mitigation:
Implement a priority zone to account for the slight bend in the shuttles path and for future vehicles that may fail to yield.

On Friday April [XXX] at 16:16 local time, the May shuttle was driving Westbound on [XXX] in Ann Arbor, MI in autonomous mode and was followed by another vehicle. The following vehicle was traveling approximately twice as fast as the May shuttle and catching up to the May shuttle from behind. The May shuttle began to slow for traffic ahead, which was stopping for a red light, but the following vehicle did not decelerate. While slowing, the May shuttle identified a bollard on the side of the road as a likely pedestrian and added a safety buffer which intersected with the predicted trajectory of the shuttle. This caused the shuttle to increase deceleration to avoid the projected collision with the buffer. The following vehicle started braking late and impacted the May shuttle from behind with a relative velocity of 6.2 m/s. Re-simulation of this event with a future software version shows that the May shuttle would have decelerated less abruptly.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: The subject Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driving in stop and go traffic on the [XXX] in Gardena, California with the L3 ADS activated. The test route selected by the driver in the vehicle's navigation system indicated an upcoming exit, so the driver began to prepare for a lane change towards the highway exit by deactivating the L3 ADS and activating the turn signal. Once the vehicle was in conventional driving mode, the driver looked for a gap in the adjacent lane to merge towards the exit lane, applied the brakes, and slowed the vehicle down. The SUV following the Mercedes-Benz vehicle did not respond in time to the vehicle's braking and contacted the rear of the Mercedes-Benz approximately 10 seconds after the L3 ADS was deactivated.  The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were driven from the scene of the incident.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: Mercedes-Benz has conducted a review of the incident and the following is based on that review. The subject Mercedes-Benz Drive Pilot test vehicle was traveling between 15-20 mph in the #2 northbound lane on the [XXX] in California in stop and go traffic with the L3 ADS activated by the driver. The vehicle's ADS determined that a truck traveling in the adjacent lane had a trajectory towards the Drive Pilot's lane, and so the Mercedes-Benz test vehicle autonomously applied the brakes to avoid a collision. After applying the brakes and bringing itself to a standstill, the Mercedes-Benz was then struck in the rear bumper by a trailing semi-truck that did not stop in time. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were able to be driven from the scene of the incident. The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper, and no damage was observed on the semi-truck at the scene. The CA Traffic Collision Report for the subject incident noted a violation of California Vehicle Code 22350 (unsafe speed for traffic conditions) by the semi-truck in the #2 lane that struck the rear bumper of the Mercedes-Benz.
